Some believe that this root derives from an Indo-European base word for [[mind]] (possibly from ''*men-'' "to think"). Additionally, Germanic words for man referred to human beings and were modified to denote sex. But during the middle ages all Germanic languages lost this feature and the words meant both all humans and just males. A similar development occurred in the development of Romance languages, with ''[[homo]]'' replacing ''[[vir]]'' as a reference to males in post-Classical Latin.

